description.text:
7/26/2017:
added the spool lock part to keep the spool holders in place if you happen to leave one of the bobbins out for whatever reason. print 2 place over bobbins where they meet up in the middle walls. press down to secure

Update: I also made an extruder bracket for the CR-10 that has an input side bowden tube receptacle as well. https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2450905

I saw a bunch of designs on here and other 3d printing websites for all different kinds of filament holders. And damn near every single one requires screw or bolts or some other parts that require me to go out and find the right size part. I figured I got a CR-10 and Onshape, why not design something that is 100% 3d printed. This design is massive. it requires at least a 300mm build surface and at least 250mm build height. Its not going to finish over night. I spent nearly 90 hours printing out everything, and that doesnt even include all the trial parts and such. This print is for the advanced user to say the least.

Note: there is a test part for the hinge pins, once you print the bottom then print out the test pin to see if you need to resize it. it should fit the first time but your printer is not my printer.

description.text:
Working with the anycubic trigorilla mainboard (a derivative of RAMPS), I've learned that these boards can run HOT. Not just the MOSFETs, but also the stepper motors - and this is in an open well cooled housing. The way the mainboard is crammed into the bed of a delta printer and then locked in with the print bed can cause the board to overheat... quickly.

So here is a simple, quick solution, to prevent overheating on an Anycubic Kossel printer trigorilla mainboard. It works with any standard 40mm fan, and M3 screws. Hope this helps.

Some paint is still needed for small details :

  • belt (black)
  • shoes (black)
  • socks (red & blue)
  • cheeks (optional) (red or pink)
  • tie (red)
  • holes in the body (optional) (light blue)

Parts can be printed as oriented, with supports for the arms and for body parts (hollow zone).
Assembly is really straighforward, and requires a bit of glue. The mouth will probably require some adjustment to fit with other parts.

The frame has been designed to eliminate the number of cut PVC pipes and enhance strength and stability. Only two PVC pipes run lengthwise, and the warp beam supports and heddle supports have been redesigned for the PVC to pass through them. There are 4 additional nuts and bolts used to fix the heddle supports in place and add even more stability.

A diagram with dimensions has been included.

Files include:

Rigid Heddle Loom Parts
Stick Shuttle
Boat Shuttle (still in development)
String Heddle Jig (uses (2x) 5mm thick bamboo chopsticks, instructions for use here: https://thelibrary.org/lochist/periodicals/bittersweet/su76g.htm)

The SketchUp file is included so users can view all the pieces and modify them if necessary.

This basic rigid heddle loom design incorporates 22mm diameter PVC pipe and two 3mm x 12mm bolts and accompanying hex nuts for the cogs and pawls.

The heddle is approximately 400mm wide.

Resources on setting up and using rigid heddle looms can be found here: https://www.ashford.co.nz/tutorials/weaving-tutorials

Assembling the heddle requires friction welding. The technique is described here: http://hackaday.com/2014/12/30/3d-printing-technique-friction-welding/

Hot glue is used to connect the printed parts with the PVC pipe. But drilling a small hole through the PVC and the 3D printed parts where they interface and inserting a pin or length of paperclip metal to pin everything together works much better. For the cog it is necessary or it will slip when under tension during weaving.

This loom project is part of a wider project seeking to bridge the gap between highly industrialized textile production and localized hand-made production.

Read more here: http://www.progressth.org/2017/07/makers-taking-on-textiles.html

I saw this Easy-Adjust Smart Phone & Tablet Stand by pwnate https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1755530 and wanted to make some tweaks to it. I increased the diameter of the device lip to make it bigger to accept tablets and made it wider to make it more stable. In addition, I added friction fit connections instead of the rubber band method of the original design.

I created two versions as I was exploring different connection types. V1 uses geared male / female parts to create a friction fit. V2 uses a pin connector that snaps the other two parts together but you can easily pull it apart to adjust and re-snap it together; geared edges keep the mating parts from rotating.

Try both versions and let me know which one you prefer!

This is a bookmark that has been specifically designed to challenge your printers. It is very thin - from 0.5 to 1 mm - where the part that  clips on the pages is just 0.5mm while the "50 micron" text is 1mm.  
On the thin clip the text is carved so that the layers are just totalling 0.25mm.  
If your print bed is not perfectly levelled, it won't print. Have a look at the skirt in one of the pictures: it is really thin (100 micron) and uniform. Get yours the same and it will print perfectly.  
Sliced at 50 micron it is made of 19 layers (the first is 100 micron).

Slice this at 0.05mm layer height and 0.35 extruder width. First layer 100 micron.
I attach an already sliced file, suitable for ptinters with a 3mm filament feed and at least 20x20cm printing plate. Temperature settings are for PLA at 216 C, but you can edit the G-Code to get it right for your filaments (look for and edit M104 and M109 instructions). Play with speeds and temperature. If you're using Slic3r, don't forget to turn on "Avoid crossing perimeters" to keep it clean.

description.text:
I figured it would be a good idea to combine both a 40mm fan heatsink fan shroud and the well known fang already modified to fit the shroud perfectly without the guess work of modifying the fang for those new to 3D printing and/or blender.

I remixed the original 40mm fan duct by loco to make it easier to snap on without breaking and stay in place without shifting up.

I also adjusted the Fang by Lion4H to fit the nozzle position and thickened the support arms connecting the fan mount to the fang arms.

This uses a 5015 radial fan and a 40x40x10mm brushless fan.

The hotend needs to be an E3d v6 or clone and the length needs to be about 46mm (minimum 45mm) from the top large fin on the heatsink to the tip of the nozzle (see included diagram). I'm using an E3D V6 clone for this.

Update 20170903 - Added a shroud with a stay on screw (see my Removeable X Carriage System - https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2515055) and an updated fan that will mount between the fan and shroud to decrease rotational momentum. Also included the blend file in case you want to print versions with the sensor mounts.

description.text:
My original lens cap for my Sony VCL-ECU2 Wide Angle adapter is somewhere in the Niagara river, so I created this replacement. This has the cutouts for the lens hood and fits nice and snug. If you use a .4mm nozzle, the walls should be solid perimeters. Be sure to print in a flexible (TPU/TPE) or similar material to keep from scratching your lens body.

This is spool holder 608 bearing mount that can be used on the FT-5 when using https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2414257 as a top frame on the printer. It requires 4 608 bearings and nuts and bolts to mount the bearings. One of the nicest things about it is that you don't have to worry about filament coming off the side of the spool when you are using a new spool. I have also included the STL that I used to print the 20x20 hollow tube that I used instead of 2020 extrusion for the frame. All you need to do when printing is adjust the Z height of the part to match the length of tube that you need. I use Simplify3D so it's easy to do in the slicer but I'm sure it is also possible using another slicer. Print it with the closed in down for good bed adhesion. I printed it out with a .8 nozzle so it didn't take me that long to make the parts.

description.text:
Was trying to learn Fusion 360 late one night and decided I wanted to make something to print on my day off. I wanted it to be something simplistic, yet useful. Had a surplus of parts from RadioShack's going out of business sale and had some things lying around from other projects and decided to make a fume extractor out of a 120mm fan. It's not elegant or pretty, but it works much better than I thought it would.

The one I built uses a USB cable for use with a phone charger or a battery pack. Don't plug it into the USB ports of your PC! It's brought up to 12v with the help of a boost converter. The filter is sandwiched between a bracket and the face plate. Another bracket is printed for the back to help keep the fan off the counter

I'm including the .f3d for anyone who wants to tweak the brackets and face plate for their own use and/or fix my stupid mistakes.

Also sorry for the messy workbench in the picture. I really need to tidy up...

Printer Brand:

Prusa

Printer:

Prusa Mk2

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

.20mm

Infill:

60%

Notes:

You could probably get away with less infill. Took me roughly an hour for each bracket and almost 3.5 hours for the face plate. Someone who knows what they're doing with their printer could probably get it done in shorter time.

Atomic Filament's Translucent Blue PLA was used in the build.

What parts did I use?

Parts listed below. Linked parts are the exact parts I used and may/may not be the best way to assemble this, so feel free to tweak for personal taste/safety.

  • 120mm computer fan purchased from Radioshack when they were still alive
  • USB cable I had lying around
  • Cheap USB wall charger brick from a gas station
  • Boost converter that takes the USB's 5v to 12v. Read the note after the list!
  • 8x M5x25 Machine Screws
  • 8x M5 washers that were used to help secure the filter, but they may not be necessary...
  • Carbon air filter cut to size
  • Auto body mesh for looks

If you plan to use the Gowoops boost converters, make sure you test the output with a multimeter BEFORE soldering up the fan. For some reason, they are set at their highest value out of the bag. This turned the 5 volts DC from the USB charger to 35 volts! Use a small flat head screwdriver to tune the potentiometer on the board until you get a solid 12 volts to work with.

I had to use a 5mm tap to make threads for the M5 machine screws in the fan mounting holes and printed parts. If looks aren't important, zipties could probably be used to the same effect. Saves time and money.

The fan's label was peeled off and the plastic underneath was roughed up with sandpaper to mount the converter with hot glue. It looks bad, but whatever.

If I could do this all over...

What would I change?

  • Make a cleaner looking back. Possibly a back plate with a place to mount the converter.
  • Use less hot glue.
  • Change the front plate to make it easier to swap out filters. Right now, the filter is just sandwiched into place.
  • Add a power switch and maybe a potentiometer to control fan speed.

Horse Trophy/Award

description.text:
I designed this Gear Fidget Spinner as I like the way hears mesh together. I was able to eliminate a center bearing and make the center entirely out of plastic. This makes for a pretty quick print overall and a little cheaper per spinner (3 bearings rather than 4).

Notice that the "center gear" is floating. There is a rim on the top and bottom of the "center gear" that suspends and centers it using the 3 gears around it.

Note that all three bearings must be functional, unlike most spinners.

Requires 3 x 608 (22mm) bearings.

Please post your makes and comments!

Use my Spinner Press to help insert the bearings. http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2275122

Notes:

Print 3 gears, 1 center gear, 1 cover pin, and 1 cover socket = 1 spinner.

Assembly
  1. Insert the bearings in each gear
  2. Slide the bearings on to the "cover sockets"
  3. Fit the center gear between the gears
  4. Press the "cover pins" in to the "cover sockets".

All parts should press together pretty easily. If the "cover pins" part is loose, you can heat and gently squeeze the pins to make them very slightly oval shaped. They will then press together firmly.

Got the Marlin 1.1.4 from github, configured and compiled it for my Anycubic Kossel Plus. Done more than 20 hours of printing using this firmware.

Change your DELTA_HEIGHT, DELTA_DIAGONAL_ROD and DEFAULT_AXIS_STEPS_PER_UNIT in Configuration.h according to your original calibration as written on the Anycubic Manual.

The Marlin 1.1.3 as the original Anycubic Firmware had the variables DELTA_SMOOTH_ROD_OFFSET, DELTA_EFFECTOR_OFFSET and DELTA_CARRIAGE_OFFSET. The subtraction of those values where the DELTA_RADIUS. That was removed in Marlin 1.1.4, one less math for the ATMega CPU to do. I'm adding a Anycubic Kossel Plus Changes.h with everything I changed from the original Marlin firmware to match the the original Anycubic firmware. Discussion and improvements are welcome here.

I kept the DELTA_SEGMENTS_PER_SECOND at 200 a default for Malin 1.1.4. That used to be 80 to 100 in old Marlins. Anycubic uses 100 there. This seens to improve circle resolution.

Also I sent this to the guys at anycubic. Hope they made good use of it.

I couldn't find a replacement windshield wiper reservoir cap for my 2013 Nissan Armada so I made one in OpenSCAD. You should be able to customize it however you want. A thickness of three mm seems to be about right (so there's probably no reason to ever change it).

The height should be a bit more (in mm) than the height you want the cap to be, at least the thickness plus the top to the bottom of the retainer ring. The diameter is the outside of the diameter of the "spout" at its widest (which is the retainer ring part). The lip should be how far inward the "lip" portion of the cap should extend toward the center, that's the part that keeps the lid on.

title: Cone Hub for SPANNERHANDS Spool System

description.text:
I loved the look of the SPANNERHANDS Spool System enclosed spool-holder, but wanted something with an adjustable / universal hub to fit all of the different brands of filament I am playing with. I designed and printed this to fit the large 1kg spool box and use the ubiquitous 608 bearings. The cone fits spools with a hub diameter between 24mm and 60mm. The width of spool that will fit inside the enclosure varies with hub diameter, from about 83mm with a 60mm hub down to around 47mm for a 24mm hub.

Parts needed:

  • Two prints of the Cone Hub
  • Two prints of the Bearing Holder
  • 100 mm length of M8 threaded rod
  • Two 608 bearings
  • 5 M8 thin nuts

Assembly:

  1. Place a drop of superglue on the outside edge of each bearing and press them into the bearing holders.
  2. Place a drop of superglue on the outside edge of 4 of the nuts and press them into the four recesses in the cone hubs.
  3. Thread the last nut onto the rod with enough protruding to fully seat in the bearing. Thread one of the cones against this nut and use it to jam lock that cone in place.

Use:

  1. Place spool against first cone.
  2. Thread on second cone and adjust to hand tight.
  3. Place one bearing on each end of threaded rod and drop into spool holder.

description.text:
This is a 3d printable Neopixel/WS2812 Strip segment LED display.

I didn't want to pay $3 for chinese clone rings and then have to make a housing, so why not put some of the cheaper LED strip on its side and have it edge-light some clear material.

This design started off as a laser cut version and I may publish that eventually, but for now here are 6mm (Neopixel Mini/SK6812 mini) and 10mm thick (standard addressable ws2812b) versions, you will need the 60 LED/m strip for this to even begin to line up. I've also used laser cut 6mm and 10mm acrylic in my printed parts for light transmission clarity but have included files inserts that you could print out of a clear plastic.

Notes:

Walls are setup for a 0.6mm nozzle. A 0.3mm would also work. I use 6 exterior layers on all faces. I would specify 12 outer layers if I had used the 0.3mm nozzle. This isn't really expected to bear any load but it does compress around the gooseneck a bit to keep from slipping. A good solid surface seems best.

I sketched the more complex face. Select the parts of the sketch to extrude. The bolt head will be about 15mm so I extruded it to a height of 20mm. And then I created a sketch that put a hole exactly in the center of the area where the bolt will go. And then extruded/cut the hole for the bolt. This is the final render of the part before sending to the 3D printer. Setup the 3D print job using Simplify3D and send it to the printer via USB. Installing the camera mount on the lamp!

title: Conversion of a portable Air Conditioner from single to dual hose design

description.text:
Most of the portable AC systems sold in local stores are single-hose models with two disadvantages compared to the dual-hose ones: limited cooling efficiency and creation of a a slight negative pressure in the room where they are installed.
The project is to build a box attached to the air intake grid of the AC unit and allowing the connection of a 2nd hose .
Due to its size, the box was divided in 4 identical parts. All the parts (box+hose connector) are made of abs and glued (abs juice) together.
Box parts and hose connector are anti warp designed.

Hose diameter: 15 cm
